{'action': 'closed', 'number': 28343, 'pull_request': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pulls/28343', 'id': 911073422, 'node_id': 'PR_kwDOACyxNM42TeCO', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/28343', 'diff_url': 'https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/28343.diff', 'patch_url': 'https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/28343.patch', 'issue_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/28343', 'number': 28343, 'state': 'closed', 'locked': False, 'title': 'Azure cosmos diagnostics memory leak fix', 'user': {'login': 'kushagraThapar', 'id': 14034156, 'node_id': 'MDQ6VXNlcjE0MDM0MTU2', 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/14034156?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/kushagraThapar', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 
* Current version of `CosmosException` refers to `CosmosDiagnostics`, which refers to `DiagnosticsClientContext` which is actually a reference to `RxDocumentClientImpl` - which exposes all information include caches, Store Models, and what not. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`
* Only exposed `DiagnosticsClientConfig` in `CosmosDiagnostics` - which is only for configs serialization. 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 
* Current version of `CosmosException` refers to `CosmosDiagnostics`, which refers to `DiagnosticsClientContext` which is actually a reference to `RxDocumentClientImpl` - which exposes all information include caches, Store Models, and what not. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`
* Only exposed `DiagnosticsClientConfig` in `CosmosDiagnostics` - which is only for configs serialization. False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 
* Current version of `CosmosException` refers to `CosmosDiagnostics`, which refers to `DiagnosticsClientContext` which is actually a reference to `RxDocumentClientImpl` - which exposes all information include caches, Store Models, and what not. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`
* Only exposed `DiagnosticsClientConfig` in `CosmosDiagnostics` - which is only for configs serialization. False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 
* Current version of `CosmosException` refers to `CosmosDiagnostics`, which refers to `DiagnosticsClientContext` which is actually a reference to `RxDocumentClientImpl` - which exposes all information include caches, Store Models, and what not. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`
* Only exposed `DiagnosticsClientConfig` in `CosmosDiagnostics` - which is only for configs serialization. False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 
* Current version of `CosmosException` refers to `CosmosDiagnostics`, which refers to `DiagnosticsClientContext` which is actually a reference to `RxDocumentClientImpl` - which exposes all information include caches, Store Models, and what not. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`
* Only exposed `DiagnosticsClientConfig` in `CosmosDiagnostics` - which is only for configs serialization. False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 
* Current version of `CosmosException` refers to `CosmosDiagnostics`, which refers to `DiagnosticsClientContext` which is actually a reference to `RxDocumentClientImpl` - which exposes all information include caches, Store Models, and what not. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`
* Only exposed `DiagnosticsClientConfig` in `CosmosDiagnostics` - which is only for configs serialization. None, 'body': "**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
Currently, there is no way to know the liveness of the ChangeFeedProcessor while the thread is running it. In the case of DB where there is a really low traffic, the handleNewChanges() will get invoked in push model which will be very staggered. 

**Describe the solution you'd like**
Push() model already retries after X sec, it will be better to have a new callback handleNoNewChanges() that will return every X seconds if there is no new changes. We can use it ensure that ChangeFeedProcessor is live and working.

False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 
* Current version of `CosmosException` refers to `CosmosDiagnostics`, which refers to `DiagnosticsClientContext` which is actually a reference to `RxDocumentClientImpl` - which exposes all information include caches, Store Models, and what not. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`
* Only exposed `DiagnosticsClientConfig` in `CosmosDiagnostics` - which is only for configs serialization. False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 
* Current version of `CosmosException` refers to `CosmosDiagnostics`, which refers to `DiagnosticsClientContext` which is actually a reference to `RxDocumentClientImpl` - which exposes all information include caches, Store Models, and what not. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`
* Only exposed `DiagnosticsClientConfig` in `CosmosDiagnostics` - which is only for configs serialization. False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 
* Current version of `CosmosException` refers to `CosmosDiagnostics`, which refers to `DiagnosticsClientContext` which is actually a reference to `RxDocumentClientImpl` - which exposes all information include caches, Store Models, and what not. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`
* Only exposed `DiagnosticsClientConfig` in `CosmosDiagnostics` - which is only for configs serialization. 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 
* Current version of `CosmosException` refers to `CosmosDiagnostics`, which refers to `DiagnosticsClientContext` which is actually a reference to `RxDocumentClientImpl` - which exposes all information include caches, Store Models, and what not. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`
* Only exposed `DiagnosticsClientConfig` in `CosmosDiagnostics` - which is only for configs serialization. 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 
* Current version of `CosmosException` refers to `CosmosDiagnostics`, which refers to `DiagnosticsClientContext` which is actually a reference to `RxDocumentClientImpl` - which exposes all information include caches, Store Models, and what not. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`
* Only exposed `DiagnosticsClientConfig` in `CosmosDiagnostics` - which is only for configs serialization. False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 
* Current version of `CosmosException` refers to `CosmosDiagnostics`, which refers to `DiagnosticsClientContext` which is actually a reference to `RxDocumentClientImpl` - which exposes all information include caches, Store Models, and what not. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`
* Only exposed `DiagnosticsClientConfig` in `CosmosDiagnostics` - which is only for configs serialization. False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 
* Current version of `CosmosException` refers to `CosmosDiagnostics`, which refers to `DiagnosticsClientContext` which is actually a reference to `RxDocumentClientImpl` - which exposes all information include caches, Store Models, and what not. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`
* Only exposed `DiagnosticsClientConfig` in `CosmosDiagnostics` - which is only for configs serialization. False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 
* Current version of `CosmosException` refers to `CosmosDiagnostics`, which refers to `DiagnosticsClientContext` which is actually a reference to `RxDocumentClientImpl` - which exposes all information include caches, Store Models, and what not. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`
* Only exposed `DiagnosticsClientConfig` in `CosmosDiagnostics` - which is only for configs serialization. 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 
* Current version of `CosmosException` refers to `CosmosDiagnostics`, which refers to `DiagnosticsClientContext` which is actually a reference to `RxDocumentClientImpl` - which exposes all information include caches, Store Models, and what not. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`
* Only exposed `DiagnosticsClientConfig` in `CosmosDiagnostics` - which is only for configs serialization. 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 
* Current version of `CosmosException` refers to `CosmosDiagnostics`, which refers to `DiagnosticsClientContext` which is actually a reference to `RxDocumentClientImpl` - which exposes all information include caches, Store Models, and what not. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`
* Only exposed `DiagnosticsClientConfig` in `CosmosDiagnostics` - which is only for configs serialization. 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 
* Current version of `CosmosException` refers to `CosmosDiagnostics`, which refers to `DiagnosticsClientContext` which is actually a reference to `RxDocumentClientImpl` - which exposes all information include caches, Store Models, and what not. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`
* Only exposed `DiagnosticsClientConfig` in `CosmosDiagnostics` - which is only for configs serialization. 'https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/28343.diff', 'patch_url': 'https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/28343.patch', 'merged_at': None}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 
* Current version of `CosmosException` refers to `CosmosDiagnostics`, which refers to `DiagnosticsClientContext` which is actually a reference to `RxDocumentClientImpl` - which exposes all information include caches, Store Models, and what not. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`
* Only exposed `DiagnosticsClientConfig` in `CosmosDiagnostics` - which is only for configs serialization. 'https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/28343.diff', 'patch_url': 'https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/28343.patch', 'merged_at': None}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics.

Easier to map the diagnostics as well. However, I have few concerns: 
1. Doing this change for AEMO, and changing too many things in one hotfix. 
2. StoreResponse and CosmosException are natively used in a lot of other diagnostics places (like Tracer, and CosmosPagedFlux, etc) - testing all of them puts a lot of extra effort, which might affect the timeline. 

In my opinion, we should re-model the diagnostics in a separate iteration, and release it after some good testing. 

Also, if we want to put that effort now, it is okay to do so, but worth discussing this in regards to AEMO timeline. False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`', 'created_at': '2022-04-15T19:54:42Z', 'updated_at': False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`', 'created_at': '2022-04-15T19:54:42Z', 'updated_at': False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`', 'created_at': '2022-04-15T19:54:42Z', 'updated_at': False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`', 'created_at': '2022-04-15T19:54:42Z', 'updated_at': False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`', 'created_at': '2022-04-15T19:54:42Z', 'updated_at': False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. 
* Removed `GlobalEndpointManager` reference from `CosmosDiagnostics` and just passed it around for capturing `regionsContacted`', 'created_at': '2022-04-15T19:54:42Z', 'updated_at': 'https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/28343.diff', 'patch_url': 'https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/28343.patch', 'merged_at': None}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `GlobalEndpointManager` which contains reference to some caches, schedulers, ExecutorService, and various other things, which makes it difficult for JVM to collect garbage diagnostics or responses. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics.

{'action': 'opened', 'number': 28343, 'pull_request': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pulls/28343', 'id': 911073422, 'node_id': 'PR_kwDOACyxNM42TeCO', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/28343', 'diff_url': 'https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/28343.diff', 'patch_url': 'https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/28343.patch', 'issue_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/28343', 'number': 28343, 'state': 'open', 'locked': False, 'title': 'Azure cosmos diagnostics memory leak fix', 'user': {'login': 'kushagraThapar', 'id': 14034156, 'node_id': 'MDQ6VXNlcjE0MDM0MTU2', 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/14034156?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/kushagraThapar', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kushagraThapar/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': 'Problems -> 

* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `storeResponseStatistics` which contains reference to `StoreResponse` which contains `CosmosDiagnostics` hence creating a circular dependency in `CosmosDiagnostics`
* Current version of `CosmosDiagnostics` contains reference to `StoreResponse` - with full byte[] content, never freeing up those byte[] content even after the response has been received from the service.
* This increases memory consumption in case of retries from SDK, since the request is maintained throughout retries, containing all the `storeResponse` with full byte[] of contents. 

Solution -> 
* Removed `CosmosDiagnostics` from `StoreResponse` as it is not required there. 
* For `CosmosResponse` types, moved `CosmosDiagnostics` to `RxDocumentServiceResponse` initializing during creation of response. 
* Created serializable versions of `StoreResponse`, `StoreResult`, and `CosmosException`, and performing a deep copy with only instance members required for diagnostics. Most issues start as that"}, {'id': 1121232256, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWwxMTIxMjMyMjU2', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/labels/Cosmos', 'name': 'Cosmos', 'color': 'e99695', 'default': False, 'description': ''}, {'id': 1178452983, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWwxMTc4NDUyOTgz', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/labels/Client', 'name': 'Client', 'color': 'ffeb77', 'default': False, 'description': 'This issue points to a problem in the data-plane of the library.'}, {'id': 1302894074, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWwxMzAyODk0MDc0', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/labels/customer-reported', 'name': 'customer-reported', 'color': '3800e0', 'default': False, 'description': 'Issues that are reported by GitHub users external to the Azure organization.'}, {'id': 2188787120, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWwyMTg4Nzg3MTIw', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/labels/azure-spring-cosmos', 'name': 'azure-spring-cosmos', 'color': '0000FF', 'default': False, 'description': 'Spring cosmos related issues.'}], 'state': 'open', 'locked': False, 'assignee': None, 'assignees': [], 'milestone': None, 'comments': 4, 'created_at': '2022-04-12T04:38:01Z', 'updated_at': '2022-04-13T17:54:21Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '**Query/Question**
We have used Cosmos to query data using both connection string and MSI. We have observed that with MSI its taking extra time to get the response and our app is running slow really slow compared to the case if we use connection string.
When reviewing the diagnostic logs from both the environments (conn string vs MSI) we saw some differences in the **QueryPlan RequestTimeline**

**With Connection String**: 
[{"eventName":"connectionAcquired","startTimeUTC":"2022-04-05T11:45:31.503Z","durationInMicroSec":0},{"eventName":"connectionConfigured","startTimeUTC":"2022-04-05T11:45:31.503Z","durationInMicroSec":0},{"eventName":"requestSent","startTimeUTC":"2022-04-05T11:45:31.503Z","durationInMicroSec":0},{"eventName":"transitTime","startTimeUTC":"2022-04-05T11:45:31.503Z","durationInMicroSec":2000},{"eventName":"received","startTimeUTC":"2022-04-05T11:45:31.505Z","durationInMicroSec":0}]

**With MSI**:
[{""eventName"":""**connectionCreated**"",""startTimeUTC"":""2022-04-11T11:08:19.097Z"",""durationInMicroSec"":**15000**},{""eventName"":""connectionConfigured"",""startTimeUTC"":""2022-04-11T11:08:19.112Z"",""durationInMicroSec"":0},{""eventName"":""requestSent"",""startTimeUTC"":""2022-04-11T11:08:19.112Z"",""durationInMicroSec"":0},{""eventName"":""transitTime"",""startTimeUTC"":""2022-04-11T11:08:19.112Z"",""durationInMicroSec"":2000},{""eventName"":""received"",""startTimeUTC"":""2022-04-11T11:08:19.114Z"",""durationInMicroSec"":0}]

When connecting to cosmos using MSI, we are seeing an extra event in the Timeline **connectionCreated** which is coming for every lookup/query we are running in our app and is taking most of the response time.
But with connection string for every lookup/query we don't see this event every time we query cosmos and directly seeing  **connectionAcquired** event.

How can we pervent this connectionCreated event when conencting to cosmos using MSI

We have used Cosmos to query data using both connection string and MSI. We have observed that with MSI its taking extra time to get the response and our app is running slow really slow compared to the case if we use connection string.
When reviewing the diagnostic logs from both the environments (conn string vs MSI) we saw some differences in the **QueryPlan RequestTimeline**

**With Connection String**: 
[{"eventName":"connectionAcquired","startTimeUTC":"2022-04-05T11:45:31.503Z","durationInMicroSec":0},{"eventName":"connectionConfigured","startTimeUTC":"2022-04-05T11:45:31.503Z","durationInMicroSec":0},{"eventName":"requestSent","startTimeUTC":"2022-04-05T11:45:31.503Z","durationInMicroSec":0},{"eventName":"transitTime","startTimeUTC":"2022-04-05T11:45:31.503Z","durationInMicroSec":2000},{"eventName":"received","startTimeUTC":"2022-04-05T11:45:31.505Z","durationInMicroSec":0}]

**With MSI**:
[{""eventName"":""**connectionCreated**"",""startTimeUTC"":""2022-04-11T11:08:19.097Z"",""durationInMicroSec"":**15000**},{""eventName"":""connectionConfigured"",""startTimeUTC"":""2022-04-11T11:08:19.112Z"",""durationInMicroSec"":0},{""eventName"":""requestSent"",""startTimeUTC"":""2022-04-11T11:08:19.112Z"",""durationInMicroSec"":0},{""eventName"":""transitTime"",""startTimeUTC"":""2022-04-11T11:08:19.112Z"",""durationInMicroSec"":2000},{""eventName"":""received"",""startTimeUTC"":""2022-04-11T11:08:19.114Z"",""durationInMicroSec"":0}]

When connecting to cosmos using MSI, we are seeing an extra event in the Timeline **connectionCreated** which is coming for every lookup/query we are running in our app and is taking most of the response time.
But with connection string for every lookup/query we don't see this event every time we query cosmos and directly seeing  **connectionAcquired** event.

How can we pervent this connectionCreated event when conencting to cosmos using MSI

***Why is this not a Bug or a feature Request?***
Not sure as of now maybe an issue/bug.

`connectionCreated` is first time when connection is created and `connectionAcquired` happens when the connection is already present, and it is just acquired from the connection pool. These don't have to do anything with MSI or connection string.. it is irrelevant. `connectionAcquired` is reusing the same connection, as it has already been created. 

Even for MSI or using connection string, in both cases, you will see first few connections as `connectionCreated` and then rest of them getting re-used and will show `connectionAcquired`.

Description

**Summary**
Currently, if throughput control controller initialized failed due to any reason, the request using throughput control will also fail. This enables the capability for customer to opt out this default behavior.

If continueOnInitError = true, request will fallback to original request flow if throughput control controller failed on initialization.
If continueOnInitError = false (also the default value), request will fail if throughput control controller failed on initialization.

How to enable continueOnInitError:
 new ThroughputControlGroupConfigBuilder()
  .setContinueOnInitError(true)

So the request flow:
request1 -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request
...
requestN -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request

## azure-cosmos
### 4.28.1 (2022-04-08)
#### Other Changes
* Updated `jackson` dependency to 2.13.2 and `jackson-databind` dependency to 2.13.2.1 - CVE-2020-36518. - See [PR 27847](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/27847)

## azure-spring-data-cosmos
### 3.19.1 (2022-04-08)
#### Other Changes
* Updated `azure-cosmos` to version `4.28.1`.

## azure-cosmos-spark
### 4.8.0 (2022-04-08)
#### Features Added
* Added an API to determine installed version of the Cosmos Spark connector (`CosmosItemsDataSource.version`/`CosmosChangeFeedDataSource.version`).See [PR 27709](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/27709)

#### Other Changes
* Reduced GC (Garbage Collection) pressure when executing queries returning many documents by pushing down type conversion. - See [PR 27440](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/27440)', ## azure-cosmos
### 4.28.1 (2022-04-08)
#### Key Bug Fixes
* Updated `jackson` dependency to 2.13.2 and `jackson-databind` dependency to 2.13.2.1 - CVE-2020-36518. - See [PR 27847](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/27847)

## azure-spring-data-cosmos
### 3.19.1 (2022-04-08)
#### Key Bug Fixes
* Updated `azure-cosmos` to version `4.28.1`.

## azure-cosmos-spark
### 4.8.0 (2022-04-08)
#### Features Added
* Added an API to determine installed version of the Cosmos Spark connector (`CosmosItemsDataSource.version`/`CosmosChangeFeedDataSource.version`).See [PR 27709](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/27709)

#### Other Changes
* Reduced GC (Garbage Collection) pressure when executing queries returning many documents by pushing down type conversion. - See [PR 27440](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/27440)', 'https://api.github.com/users/simorenoh/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/simorenoh/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': 'This PR has the changes for the async client to utilize AAD authentication.

The way the @azure.identity package uses AAD credentials to authenticate services is by adding those credentials into a policy that runs when requests are sent to the core pipelines. This policy makes sure to refresh the current token if needed and set the authentication header of requests going to the pipeline. The reason why Cosmos had to create their own policy in this instance is due to the prefix we utilize for our tokens, since the bearer token policy given by the identity module sends a different prefix altogether and as such does not work for us.

It was also recommended by the identity team to create our own policies entirely rather than attempting to override a couple methods, since this could break us on their end - specially for the `_update_headers()` method since it's private.

For the async client, the credentials seem to also require their context managers to be in place in order to not run into "Unclosed client session" errors once the context is over. Looks kindda weird with the double `async with`, so if there's any suggestions on this do let me know.

Sample is a simple run-through of what can and can't be done, if you think adding more examples would be helpful I can do so as well.', 'created_at': '2022-03-28T23:53:20Z', 'updated_at': 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/simorenoh/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': 'This PR has the changes for the async client to utilize AAD authentication.

The way the @azure.identity package uses AAD credentials to authenticate services is by adding those credentials into a policy that runs when requests are sent to the core pipelines. This policy makes sure to refresh the current token if needed and set the authentication header of requests going to the pipeline. The reason why Cosmos had to create their own policy in this instance is due to the prefix we utilize for our tokens, since the bearer token policy given by the identity module sends a different prefix altogether and as such does not work for us.

It was also recommended by the identity team to create our own policies entirely rather than attempting to override a couple methods, since this could break us on their end - specially for the `_update_headers()` method since it's private.

For the async client, the credentials seem to also require their context managers to be in place in order to not run into "Unclosed client session" errors once the context is over. Looks kindda weird with the double `async with`, so if there's any suggestions on this do let me know.

Sample is a simple run-through of what can and can't be done, if you think adding more examples would be helpful I can do so as well.', 'created_at': '2022-03-28T23:53:20Z', 'updated_at': 'https://api.github.com/users/simorenoh/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/simorenoh/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': 'This PR has the changes for the async client to utilize AAD authentication.

The way the @azure.identity package uses AAD credentials to authenticate services is by adding those credentials into a policy that runs when requests are sent to the core pipelines. This policy makes sure to refresh the current token if needed and set the authentication header of requests going to the pipeline. The reason why Cosmos had to create their own policy in this instance is due to the prefix we utilize for our tokens, since the bearer token policy given by the identity module sends a different prefix altogether and as such does not work for us.

It was also recommended by the identity team to create our own policies entirely rather than attempting to override a couple methods, since this could break us on their end - specially for the `_update_headers()` method since it's private.

For the async client, the credentials seem to also require their context managers to be in place in order to not run into "Unclosed client session" errors once the context is over. Looks kindda weird with the double `async with`, so if there's any suggestions on this do let me know.

Sample is a simple run-through of what can and can't be done, if you think adding more examples would be helpful I can do so as well.', 'created_at': '2022-03-28T23:53:20Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-24T17:35:55Z', 'closed_at': '2022-03-24T17:35:55Z', 'author_association': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': "## Description

In various parts of the source and sink connectors, there is logging of the record verbatim. This ends up often being written to logs and aggregated by downstream applications and may end up persisting customer sensitive PII in undesirable places such as Kibana. Even though many places are logging at very low level (`TRACE` or `DEBUG`) , these could still be aggregated with the logging strategy is configured to be more aggressive.

## Expected Behavior

Don't ever log user data verbatim.

## Reproduce

1. Enable `TRACE` level debugging for the connector using [REST API](https://rmoff.net/2020/01/16/changing-the-logging-level-for-kafka-connect-dynamically/)
2. Observe user records being written to logs

## Additional Context

Description

**Summary**
Currently, if throughput control controller initialized failed due to any reason, the request using throughput control will also fail. This enables the capacity for customer to opt out this default behavior.

If continueOnInitError = true, request will fallback to original request flow if throughput control controller failed on initialization.
If continueOnInitError = false (also the default value), request will fail if throughput control controller failed on initialization.

How to enable continueOnInitError:
 new ThroughputControlGroupConfigBuilder()
  .setContinueOnInitError(true)

So the request flow:
request1 -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request
...
requestN -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request

Description

**Summary**
Currently, if throughput control controller initialized failed due to any reason, the request using throughput control will also fail. This enables the capacity for customer to opt out this default behavior.

If continueOnInitError = true, request will fallback to original request flow if throughput control controller failed on initialization.
If continueOnInitError = false (also the default value), request will fail if throughput control controller failed on initialization.

How to enable continueOnInitError:
 new ThroughputControlGroupConfigBuilder()
  .setContinueOnInitError(true)

So the request flow:
request1 -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request
...
requestN -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request

Description

**Summary**
Currently, if throughput control controller initialized failed due to any reason, the request using throughput control will also fail. This enables the capacity for customer to opt out this default behavior.

If continueOnInitError = true, request will fallback to original request flow if throughput control controller failed on initialization.
If continueOnInitError = false (also the default value), request will fail if throughput control controller failed on initialization.

How to enable continueOnInitError:
 new ThroughputControlGroupConfigBuilder()
  .setContinueOnInitError(true)

So the request flow:
request1 -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request
...
requestN -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request

Description

**Summary**
Currently, if throughput control controller initialized failed due to any reason, the request using throughput control will also fail. This enables the capacity for customer to opt out this default behavior.

If continueOnInitError = true, request will fallback to original request flow if throughput control controller failed on initialization.
If continueOnInitError = false (also the default value), request will fail if throughput control controller failed on initialization.

How to enable continueOnInitError:
 new ThroughputControlGroupConfigBuilder()
  .setContinueOnInitError(true)

So the request flow:
request1 -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request
...
requestN -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request

Description

**Summary**
Currently, if throughput control controller initialized failed due to any reason, the request using throughput control will also fail. This enables the capacity for customer to opt out this default behavior.

If continueOnInitError = true, request will fallback to original request flow if throughput control controller failed on initialization.
If continueOnInitError = false (also the default value), request will fail if throughput control controller failed on initialization.

How to enable continueOnInitError:
 new ThroughputControlGroupConfigBuilder()
  .setContinueOnInitError(true)

So the request flow:
request1 -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request
...
requestN -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request

'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/xinlian12/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '# Description

**Summary**
Currently, if throughput control controller initialized failed due to any reason, the request using throughput control will also fail. This enables the capacity for customer to opt out this default behavior.

If continueOnInitError = true, request will fallback to original request flow if throughput control controller failed on initialization.
If continueOnInitError = false (also the default value), request will fail if throughput control controller failed on initialization.

How to enable continueOnInitError:
 new ThroughputControlGroupConfigBuilder()
  .setContinueOnInitError(true)

So the request flow:
request1 -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request
...
requestN -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request

'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/xinlian12/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '# Description

**Summary**
Currently, if throughput control controller initialized failed due to any reason, the request using throughput control will also fail. This enables the capacity for customer to opt out this default behavior.

If continueOnInitError = true, request will fallback to original request flow if throughput control controller failed on initialization.
If continueOnInitError = false (also the default value), request will fail if throughput control controller failed on initialization.

How to enable continueOnInitError:
 new ThroughputControlGroupConfigBuilder()
  .setContinueOnInitError(true)

So the request flow:
request1 -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request
...
requestN -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request

'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/xinlian12/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '# Description

**Summary**
Currently, if throughput control controller initialized failed due to any reason, the request using throughput control will also fail. This enables the capacity for customer to opt out this default behavior.

If continueOnInitError = true, request will fallback to original request flow if throughput control controller failed on initialization.
If continueOnInitError = false (also the default value), request will fail if throughput control controller failed on initialization.

How to enable continueOnInitError:
 new ThroughputControlGroupConfigBuilder()
  .setContinueOnInitError(true)

So the request flow:
request1 -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request
...
requestN -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request

'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/xinlian12/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '# Description

**Summary**
Currently, if throughput control controller initialized failed due to any reason, the request using throughput control will also fail. This enables the capacity for customer to opt out this default behavior.

If continueOnInitError = true, request will fallback to original request flow if throughput control controller failed on initialization.
If continueOnInitError = false (also the default value), request will fail if throughput control controller failed on initialization.

How to enable continueOnInitError:
 new ThroughputControlGroupConfigBuilder()
  .setContinueOnInitError(true)

So the request flow:
request1 -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request
...
requestN -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request

Description

**Summary**
Currently, if throughput control controller initialized failed due to any reason, the request using throughput control will also fail. This enables the capacity for customer to opt out this default behavior.

If continueOnInitError = true, request will fallback to original request flow if throughput control controller failed on initialization.
If continueOnInitError = false (also the default value), request will fail if throughput control controller failed on initialization.

How to enable continueOnInitError:
 new ThroughputControlGroupConfigBuilder()
  .setContinueOnInitError(true)

So the request flow:
request1 -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request
...
requestN -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request

Description

**Summary**
Currently, if throughput control controller initialized failed due to any reason, the request using throughput control will also fail. This enables the capacity for customer to opt out this default behavior.

If continueOnInitError = true, request will fallback to original request flow if throughput control controller failed on initialization.
If continueOnInitError = false (also the default value), request will fail if throughput control controller failed on initialization.

How to enable continueOnInitError:
 new ThroughputControlGroupConfigBuilder()
  .setContinueOnInitError(true)

So the request flow:
request1 -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request
...
requestN -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request

Description

**Summary**
Currently, if throughput control controller initialized failed due to any reason, the request using throughput control will also fail. This enables the capacity for customer to opt out this default behavior.

If continueOnInitError = true, request will fallback to original request flow if throughput control controller failed on initialization.
If continueOnInitError = false (also the default value), request will fail if throughput control controller failed on initialization.

How to enable continueOnInitError:
 new ThroughputControlGroupConfigBuilder()
  .setContinueOnInitError(true)

So the request flow:
request1 -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request
...
requestN -> throughputcontrolStore -> initialize all underlying controllers -> failed -> fallbackOnInitError ? -> yes, fallback to original request flow, no fail the request

'https://api.github.com/users/FabianMeiswinkel/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '# Description
A few times a question form customers came up what the quickest way would be to check which version of the Cosmos Spark Connector is installed (especially on Synapse where customers don't necessarily need to install it manually but can use the pre-installed (probably "old") version pre-installed on the image.
This PR adds a simple API to retrieve the version that we can also extend to the OLAP connector if desired.

A few times a question form customers came up what the quickest way would be to check which version of the Cosmos Spark Connector is installed (especially on Synapse where customers don't necessarily need to install it manually but can use the pre-installed (probably "old") version pre-installed on the image.
This PR adds a simple API to retrieve the version that we can also extend to the OLAP connector if desired.

'https://api.github.com/users/FabianMeiswinkel/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '# Description
A few times a question form customers came up what the quickest way would be to check which version of the Cosmos Spark Connector is installed (especially on Synapse where customers don't necessarily need to install it manually but can use the pre-installed (probably "old") version pre-installed on the image.
This PR adds a simple API to retrieve the version that we can also extend to the OLAP connector if desired.

A few times a question form customers came up what the quickest way would be to check which version of the Cosmos Spark Connector is installed (especially on Synapse where customers don't necessarily need to install it manually but can use the pre-installed (probably "old") version pre-installed on the image.
This PR adds a simple API to retrieve the version that we can also extend to the OLAP connector if desired.
